                                                                      FY 2026 President's Budget Submission
                                                                        Operation and Maintenance, Navy
                                                            Budget Activity: Administration and Servicewide Activities
                                                           Activity Group: Logistics Operations And Technical Support
                                                         Detail by Subactivity Group: Acquisition Workforce Development
I. Description of Operations Financed:
This activity group provides for the operations of various programs that are responsible for acquisition, program management, and other operational support to the Department of
the Navy (DON). The programs represented in this activity group are Director Acquisition Talent Management (DATM), the Naval Acquisition Career Center (NACC), the Naval
Acquisition Developmental Program (NADP), and the Director of Acquisition Career Management – Management Information System (DACM-MIS). Each major program is
described below:

Director Acquisition Talent Management (DATM): The DATM is responsible for the development and implementation of DON Acquisition Workforce policies and programs.
One of the goals of these acquisition initiatives is to streamline and improve processes for greater efficiency and effectiveness in the acquisition and procurement of Navy systems,
and to disseminate information (real time) concerning acquisition regulations to all activities that are in the business of procuring for the Navy. ASN(RD&A) provides for
operation and innovation efforts, enhancements to acquisition systems that provide more detailed and accurate design/reliability assessments, data analytics, and accelerated
acquisition.

DATM oversees DON efforts to manage and improve the acquisition workforce and distributes funding received in support of the DON Acquisition Workforce (AWF) to bolster
recruiting, hiring, training, development, retention, and recognition of the AWF. These funds allow the DON to align the AWF with the strategic objective to build a workforce to
compete and win. Funds are used in support of the Naval Acquisition Development Program (NADP), workforce development and training efforts, highly qualified experts (HQEs)
to further AWF mission objectives and to maintain and upgrade business systems required by law (title 10 chapter 87). The NADP employs recent college graduates (primarily
outstanding scholars) or personnel with equivalent qualifications and develops employees through a highly structured program of education, training, rotational assignments, and
continuous learning activities. Upon graduation, entry level personnel replenish the DON acquisition workforce. Additionally, funds are used in efforts to track, train, educate, and
certify the AWF. This enables retention through the Acquisition Workforce Tuition Assistance Program (AWTAP) and training opportunities to support acquisition workforce
objectives.

Naval Acquisition Career Center (NACC): The NACC is responsible for executing the administrative support for the Naval Acquisition Workforce. Civilian Education and
Training program for the DON Director of Acquisition Talent Management (DATM). The DATM issues policy guidelines to the NACC, which executes the program management
and support functions to accomplish the DATM mission. The NACC supports functions such as the Naval Acquisition Development Program (NADP), the Acquisition Workforce
Tuition Assistance Program (AWTAP), and the ASN (RD&A) SIGMA Rotation Program and Secretary of Defense Executive Fellows (SDEF). The NADP program hires 500-700
new trainees each fiscal year and, manages the multi-year program's career development, technical training, and certification of more than 1,700 entry-level in the multi-year
program. In addition, the NACC also provides administrative support, registration, and travel management for more than 54,000 members of the AWF attending the Defense
Acquisition University (DAU) and manages the electronic data repository and interactive electronic tools required to track and retain AWF member certifications, achievements,
educational transcripts, and relative data. These programs were established as a result of Defense Acquisition Workforce Improvement Act (DAWIA) and are codified in USC 10,
Chapter 87 to sustain, develop, and enhance the professionalism of the business and technical skills of the acquisition workforce.

The Naval Acquisition Developmental Program (NADP): The Naval Acquisition Developmental Program (NADP) includes funding for the Assistant Secretary of the Navy
(Research, Development, and Acquisition (ASN, RD&A) centrally managed by Naval Acquisition Developmental Program (NADP) and the Acquisition Workforce Tuition
Assistance Program (AWTAP). Required by the Defense Acquisition Workforce Improvement Act (DAWIA) (PL 101-510), the NADP provides for centralized recruiting, hiring,
development placement of entry level employees in the following back to the basic functional areas: Program Management, Contracting, Business Financial Management,
Business Cost Estimating, Lifecycle Logistics, Engineering and Technical Management, Test and Evaluation.
The Naval Acquisition Development Program (NADP) employs recent college graduates (primarily outstanding scholars) or personnel with equivalent qualifications developed
through highly structured, two year, two and a half or three-year program of education, training, rotational assignments, and continuous learning activities. Upon graduation, entry

